<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?t=26&amp;p=72#p72"><![CDATA[
I'm currently doing a short relaunch advert to put onto YouTube, and for a laugh I'm doing it as full 1080p HD. One unanticipated side-effect is just how large the video file is at the end of processing: about 4MB per second of video, and seeing as this advert is 1min58sec, the ~472MB file takes a bloody long time to process and upload onto YouTube.<br /><br />Yes, I don't own any HD equipment at home, and even my most powerful computer cannot play this video smoothly, so I have to upload it privately to YouTube just to preview the thing! YT's own 320p downgrade isn't perfect, but it's watchable. It's also poor enough to convince me to generate and upload an equivalent DVD-quality video to YT as well as the BluRay-quality one as the test DVD video file played back very smoothly on YT.<br /><br />Then there's the source image files - you can't skimp on the resolution of these files any more! Take a look at this frame:<br /><br /><img src="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/fscratch/burst_frame.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />The adverts themselves are just over 1000 pixels high so look fine as part of a 1920x1080 image, but those 16x16 icons... yikes...! Fortunately they're fast-moving objects, so they're recognizable even though they don't spend too much time on-screen.<br /><br />The icons are from the &quot;Share This Anywhere&quot; menu you get at the top each webpage - there are over 370 ways to share this page using this app! Blimey.<br /><br />Still, the adverts look <span style="font-weight: bold">fantastic</span> in the full-sized 1920x1080 frame,<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=54">NickH</a> — Thu Jun 30, 2011 2:24 pm</p><hr />
