<title type="html"><![CDATA[The Your Sinclair Rock'n'Roll Years • Frontlines - July 2011]]></title>

<category term="The Your Sinclair Rock'n'Roll Years" scheme="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewforum.php?f=2" label="The Your Sinclair Rock'n'Roll Years"/>
<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?t=24&amp;p=51#p51"><![CDATA[
Welcome to the first Frontlines, what will hopefully be a monthly feature containing my own meanderings plus news from the scene.<br /><br />So here it is, the relaunch of the Your Sinclair Rock'n'Roll Years website - not so much a relaunch, more a change of direction. The website will be celebrating its 15th anniversary next year, but it needed bringing up to date a little to reflect the changing ways that people are accessing it.<br /><br />Gone are the days when websites survived solely on word-of-mouth, FAQs, webrings and link lists. These days the YSRnRY gets its traffic mainly from search engines, social networks and non-Sinclair-related forums, meaning that people rarely come through the front door and know what the site's about and what it has to offer.<br /><br />So, the website design's been rejigged a little to integrate it all with each other. The highlights are now promoted at the top of each page so that visitors who come in via a side entrance still know what the site has to offer. There's also a presence on Facebook and Twitter - currently just the YS Daily Fix and site news on there, but there'll be other stuff over time.<br /><br />With most of the traffic coming from outside of the Sinclair &quot;scene&quot;, it looks as if there's plenty of casual retrogamers out there, possibly looking for a place to hang out in and celebrate the Sinclair machines in their own way, so a new set of forums have been installed on this website for them. Aimed at the more casual user (although everyone is welcome to join in), I intend it to be a light, friendly forum for people to enjoy in order to get away from Real Life Stuff - I find that surrounding myself with enthusiasts having a good time rather fun, and I'm sure you will do too. <br /><br />And why not join in creating something for the scene? It could be just a webpage here, and article there, or maybe even an online book. Maybe it wouldn't involve the written word at all and be a piece of software, or some music, or a video. Hell, if you're feeling artistic, then maybe a piece of art like a painting, a model, or sculpture. Anything goes, really, as it all helps to add to a rich, varied and enjoyable hobby.<br /><br />The payoff? Creating the YSRnRY has been a joy, and wallowing in old Speccy memories is seriously good for the soul. Sharing these memories with others not only reinforces them, but you share in the warm glow of others as they relate to you memories of their own. And remember, if you enjoy creating something, chances are someone else will enjoy seeing the results.<br /><br />As for me, well, Real Life Stuff seems to grow as I get older, but I'm still working on various things after a few months' hiatus. The Documentary will get a starting chapter and a finishing double chapter, hopefully done by the end of 2012 as that year marks all sorts of different anniversaries. I'll be posting up a new Frontlines entry on here every month or so, and will also report any news that comes my way. Above all, I'm going to have a bit of fun doing things that I hope you will enjoy seeing.<br /><br />====== [ NEWS ] ======<br /><br />How's that for a fancy header?! This relaunch has been ages in the making, and I <span style="font-style: italic">still</span> haven't done everything! Still, it's a bit retro - reminds me of the fanzines, tapezines and diskzines from way-back-when. Anyway, as this is the first News section, I'll just touch upon a few things you may have missed. If you'd like your project to feature in the next one, <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/email.htm" class="postlink">email me</a> and I'll put it in. Anything goes, so long as it's vaguely Sinclair or SAM related.<br /><br />== [ TOM-CAT'S RE-CRACKS ] ==<br /><br />OK, I'm sticking to the layout (such as it is) for now as it's growing on me! Tomaz Kac has a nifty sideline in modifying games to improve them by doing things like adding training modes, 128k music to 48k games, and my particular favourite, turning 48k multiload games into 128k single loaders. No more faffing around with TZX browsers! Playing Killed Until Dead is now a totally joyful experience - <a href="http://retrospec.sgn.net/users/tomcat/yu/TRDosReCracks.php" class="postlink">take a look at the games list</a> and see what tickles your fancy. And of course, if you still use original 128k Spectrums, you can record many of these to tape to load them yourself.<br /><br />== [ MONKEY BUSINESS ] ==<br /><br />Patrick Furlong's dropped me a line to say that a new demo of Monkey Island Adventure is in the works. It is based on Part 2 of 'The Secret of Monkey Island' and sees you on your second hand ship making your way to Monkey Island. Sounds like a nice bit of interactive fan fiction - sigh, I remember when we used to call them &quot;text adventures&quot; back in the day. Did you know that Ekim Drarreg is now a travel writer? People pay him to go around the world having a wonderful time on the precondition that he writes about it when he gets back. Not that I'm jealous or anything. Oh no. Moving swiftly on...<br /><br />== [ DUNC'S BACK ] ==<br /><br /><a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/advancedlownmowersimulation.htm" class="postlink">Advanced Lawnmower Simulator</a> <span style="font-style: italic">still</span> has cult status to this day - one of those wonderful YSisms which has stood the test of time. A quick Google shows it's been remade over and over again, including <a href="http://www.youmustbejoking.demon.co.uk/als/" class="postlink">an online version</a>! Duncan MacDonald deserves the blame and the kudos for creating ALS back in 1988, and he's <a href="http://twitter.com/#!/LordScumland" class="postlink">resurfaced with a Twitter feed</a> with thoughts and jokes, such as:<br /><div class="ca-bbcode"><div class="ca-bbcode2 ca-quote"><blockquote class="uncited"><div><br />19th Century Word Club: DISGUISED IN WINE. (Drunk). Usage: &quot;I regret my behaviour of yesterday, sir. I was somewhat disguised in wine.&quot;<br /></div></blockquote></div></div><br /><br />== [ REMEMBER RETROSPEC? ] ==<br /><br />The truth is they never went away. Little was heard from them on the Speccy forums since the launch of their superlative <a href="http://retrospec.sgn.net/game/hoh" class="postlink">Head Over Heels</a> remake, but they've been really busy. There's <a href="http://retrospec.sgn.net/game/batman" class="postlink">BatMan</a> (<a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b2uXAc09av8" class="postlink">short bit of YouTube footage</a>) (a remake of the 1986 3D game) by Tomaz Kac, and <a href="http://retrospec.sgn.net/game/kl" class="postlink">KnightLore</a> (<a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ng-hseoEIhY" class="postlink">YouTube footage</a>) by Peter Hanratty for a start. There's plenty more where they came from. Old hands who remember Richard Jordan's Skool Daze/Back To Skool remake <a href="http://retrospec.sgn.net/game/ko99" class="postlink">Klass Of '99</a> may also be interested that he later went on to mash it up with HyperSports and Decathlon to create <a href="http://retrospec.sgn.net/game/sportsdaze" class="postlink">SportzDaze</a> - watching the <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LJM4YjS4cRk" class="postlink">YouTube video</a> of it brought a real smile to my face. You wait til you see the twist on HyperSports' archery event!<br /><br />== [ CRASHBACK ] ==<br /><br />There's a CRASH fan on Twitter who has been posting up <a href="http://twitter.com/#!/CrashOnlineUK" class="postlink">lots of CRASH goodness</a> from themed links through to general Speccy japery. Well worth a look.<br /><br />== [ THE LIST OF MOST IMPORTANT GAMES EVER - UNTIL THE NEXT ONE ] ==<br /><br />One of the things this site would like to do is promote everything and anything Sinclair or SAM-related - it doesn't have to be something megahuge, just something you enjoy because chances are someone else will enjoy it too. James Moffat's writing a series on what he considers the most important computer games of all time accross all formats, and the Speccy features quite nicely. <a href="http://jayodoom.blogspot.com/2011/05/my-most-important-games-ever-part-i.html" class="postlink">Here's the first part.</a><br /><br />== [ SPECTACULATOR ON iEVERYTHING ] ==<br /><br />Jonathan Needle (<a href="http://twitter.com/#!/jonathan_needle" class="postlink">Twitter</a>|<a href="http://www.facebook.com/spectaculator" class="postlink">Facebook</a>) has produced a version of his Spectaculator Spectrum emulator that is available for the iPhone and iPad, and it transferable between the two. That's what I love about the emulator writers - no matter the platform, you'll still be able to play Manic Miner on it! If you have an iThingummy, it's rather reasonably priced.<br /><br />== [ GOT NEWS? EMAIL US! ] ==<br /><br />And that's it for the first Frontlines. If you have any news for the next one (start of August), <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/email.htm" class="postlink">email me</a> and I'll put it in.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=54">NickH</a> — Sun Jun 26, 2011 7:10 pm</p><hr />
